{"title_page": "Madison Prespakis", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Madison Prespakis\n| image = Madison Prespakis 2019.2.jpg\n| caption = Prespakis playing for Carlton's VFLW team in 2019\n| fullname = Madison Prespakis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|11|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| originalteam = {{VFLW MU}} ([[VFL Women's|VFLW]])\n| draftpick  = No. 3, [[2018 AFL Women's draft#Draft|2018 national draft]]\n| debutdate = Round 1, 2019\n| debutteam = {{AFLW Car}}\n| debutopponent = {{AFLW NM}}\n| debutstadium = [[North Hobart Oval]]\n| height = 164&nbsp;cm\n| position = [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = {{AFLW Car}}\n| guernsey = 4\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| club1 = {{AFLW Car}}\n| games_goals1 = 16 (10)\n| statsend = the 2020 season\n| careerhighlights =\n* [[AFL Women's All-Australian team]]: [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team|2019]]\n* 2\u00d7 [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]]: 2019, 2020\n* [[AFL Women's Rising Star]]: [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star|2019]]\n* AFLW Players' best first-year player: 2019\n}}\n\n'''Madison Prespakis''' (born 2 November 2000) is an [[Australian rules football]]er playing for [[Carlton Football Club#AFL Women's team|Carlton Football Club]] in the [[AFL Women's]] (AFLW). A midfielder who won multiple accolades at junior level and played in the [[VFL Women's]] (VFLW) as a teenager, Prespakis won the [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star]] award and [[AFL Women's All-Australian team|AFL Women's All-Australian]] selection in 2019, and is a dual [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]] winner.\n\n== Early life ==\nPrespakis is the daughter of Damien and Jody.<ref name='Black AFL.com.au'>{{cite news |last1=Black |first1=Sarah |title=AFLW: From Auskick to likely top-three pick |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2018-10-21/aflw-from-auskick-to-likely-top-three-pick |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=21 October 2018}}</ref><ref name='McGowan AFL.com.au'>{{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Marc |title=AFLW: New Blue happy to be close to home |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2018-10-23/aflw-new-blue-happy-to-be-close-to-home |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> Her mother is an [[Indigenous Australian]] from the [[Djadjawurrung]] tribe.<ref name='McGowan AFL.com.au/> Prespakis has three siblings: twin sister Annalea, Georgie, and Jimmy.<ref name='Black AFL.com.au'/> She attended [[Gisborne Secondary College]] and supported {{AFL Ess}} growing up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Barry |title=Sunbury teen Maddy inspired to join AFLW ranks |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/north-west/sunbury-teen-maddy-inspired-to-join-aflw-ranks/news-story/780b869a1230e2bb4407a150ffe148fa |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=Sunbury Leader |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 June 2017}}</ref>\nPrespakis began playing football at four years old through the [[Auskick]] program in [[Romsey, Victoria|Romsey]], north-west of [[Melbourne]]. She played in boys' teams at first, before representing the under-15 [[Sunbury Football Netball Club|Sunbury]] girls side.<ref name='canberra times'>{{cite news |last1=Fowler |first1=Michael |title=Debut 15 years in the making for AFLW's new breed of role model |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/afl/debut-15-years-in-the-making-for-aflw-s-new-breed-of-role-model-20190207-p50w8t.html?ref=rss |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Prespakis played in the premiership-winning [[Calder Cannons]] side in the [[NAB League#NAB League Girls|TAC Cup Girls]].<ref name='AFL Vic 2017'>{{cite news |title=Calder TAC Cup Premiers |url=https://aflvic.com.au/calder-tac-cup-girls-premiers/ |accessdate=26 February 2019 |work=aflvic.com.au |publisher=AFL Victoria |date=10 May 2017}}</ref> She was named in the league's team of the year<ref name='draft watch'/> and placed second in the league's [[best and fairest]] with 20 votes.<ref name='AFL Vic 2017'/> She competed at the [[2017 AFL Women's Under 18 Championships]] for Vic Metro and was named in the All-Australian squad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Black |first1=Sarah |title=AFLW U18 All Australian squad named |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-07-18/aflw-u18-all-australian-squad-named |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=18 July 2017}}</ref> In October, Prespakis was named in the 2018 AFLW Academy squad as one of twenty-nine seventeen-year-old prospects. As part of this squad, she trained with the {{AFLW WB}} and {{AFLW Col}} over the following months.<ref>{{cite news |title=AFLW: 2018 Academy prospects revealed |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-10-25/aflw-2018-academy-prospects-revealed |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=25 October 2017}}</ref><ref name='canberra times'/>\n\nIn 2018, Prespakis became captain of the Calder Cannons<ref name='draft watch'>{{cite news |title=AFLW Draft Watch: Madison Prespakis |url=https://taccup.com.au/aflw-draft-watch-madison-prespakis/ |accessdate=15 February 2019 |work=taccup.com.au |publisher=AFL Victoria |date=15 October 2018}}</ref> and won their best and fairest award with 113 out of a possible 120 votes.<ref name='pick 3'>{{cite news |last1=Balales |first1=Danielle |title=Pick 3: Madison Prespakis |url=https://www.carltonfc.com.au/news/2018-10-23/pick-3-madison-prespakis |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=carltonfc.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> She was again named in the TAC Cup Girls Team of the Year and tied with [[Nina Morrison]] for the league best and fairest. She again competed at the [[2018 AFL Women's Under 18 Championships]]; she shared the competition's most valuable player award with Morrison on 16 votes apiece, won Vic Metro's most valuable player award and was named in the All-Australian side.<ref name='fox exhibition'>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft: Potential top picks star in U18 All-Stars exhibition match |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/aflw-draft-potential-top-picks-star-in-u18-allstars-exhibition-match/news-story/57d9a17516a0d749f650acf48fcc9d65 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=1 September 2018}}</ref><ref name='fox TAC Cup'/> She played in an [[exhibition game]] for Victoria, acting as a curtain raiser for the [[E. J. Whitten Legends Game]]. Prespakis amassed 21 disposals in Victoria's win, the most of any player.<ref name='fox exhibition'/> Aside from under-18 competitions, she also played six matches for {{VFLW MU}} in the [[VFL Women's]] (VFLW).<ref name='fox TAC Cup'>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft 2018: Future stars Nina Morrison and Madison Prespakis share in TAC Cup\u2019s top award |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/aflw-draft-2018-future-stars-nina-morrison-and-madison-prespakis-share-in-tac-cups-top-award/news-story/a0b4249c370a614db0609caec49bc89e |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2018 AFL Women's draft]], Prespakis was widely predicted to be taken with one of the first selections.<ref name=\"Black AFL.com.au\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft 2018: Full first-round mock draft for AFL women's draft |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/aflw-draft-2018-full-firstround-mock-draft-for-afl-womens-draft/news-story/44fa870081e188854ea3ee01b03e0374 |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 October 2018}}</ref> Prospective draftees were required to nominate a state or region they wished to play in; Prespakis selected the Melbourne metropolitan area, citing a wish to remain home with her family. This prevented {{AFLW Gee}} from recruiting her with pick one or two and allowed Carlton the opportunity to select her with pick three.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sewell |first1=Eliza |title=Carlton in box seat to land talented midfielder Madison Prespakis in AFLW draft |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/aflw/carlton-in-box-seat-to-land-talented-midfielder-madison-prespakis-in-aflw-draft/news-story/3b44de04df50799d5132d7216de95551 |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==AFL Women's career==\n[[File:Madison Prespakis 23.03.19 (cropped).jpg|thumb|175px|Prespakis playing for Carlton in 2019]]\nCarlton recruited Prespakis with their first selection and third overall in the 2018 AFL Women's draft.<ref name='pick 3'/> She made her AFL Women's debut in the opening round of the 2019 season against {{AFLW NM}} at [[North Hobart Oval]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Warren|first=Stu|title=Match report: Roos thrash Blues on memorable debut|url=https://womens.afl/news/15891/match-report-roos-thrash-blues-on-memorable-debut|work=womens.afl|date=3 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> The following round, she was nominated for the [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star]] award after kicking one goal and amassing 20 disposals, seven clearances and nine contested possessions against {{AFLW Ade}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olsson-Young|first=Marni|title=Blue, Docker take out round-two Rising Star nominations|url=https://womens.afl/news/16388/blue-docker-take-out-round-two-rising-star-nominations|work=womens.afl|date=12 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Prespakis went on to play in the [[2019 AFL Women's Grand Final]] loss to Adelaide in front of a record AFL Women's crowd, and was among Carlton's best players.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=Crows soar to flag in front of record crowd, but injury hits superstar|url=https://womens.afl/news/17614/crows-soar-to-flag-in-front-of-record-crowd-but-injury-hits-superstar|work=womens.afl|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> Following a debut season in which she averaged 19 disposals and kicked seven goals across nine games,<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=How will Blues replace ex-skipper after shock move to arch rivals?|url=https://womens.afl/news/40184/how-will-blues-replace-ex-skipper-after-shock-move-to-arch-rivals-|work=womens.afl|date=28 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> Prespakis won the 2019 AFL Women's Rising Star award with 49 votes and was named in the [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Navaratnam|first=Dinny|title=Five Crows, four Roos headline All Australian team|url=https://womens.afl/news/17673/five-crows-four-roos-headline-all-australian-team|work=womens.afl|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> She also won the AFLW Players' best first-year player award<ref>{{cite news|last1=Black|first1=Sarah|author2=[[Australian Associated Press]]|title=Superstar Crow clinches second MVP award|url=https://womens.afl/news/17658/superstar-crow-clinches-second-mvp-award|work=womens.afl|date=1 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> and tied for the [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]] award with captain [[Brianna Davey]], capping off a memorable first season.<ref>{{cite news|title=First-year Blue ties with skipper to win best and fairest|url=https://womens.afl/news/17794/first-year-blue-ties-with-skipper-to-win-best-and-fairest|work=womens.afl|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeading into the 2020 season, ''womens.afl'' journalist Sarah Black named Prespakis at no. 23 on her list of the top 30 players in the AFLW.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Sarah Black's top 30: Young Blue bolts into No.23|url=https://womens.afl/news/40286/sarah-black-s-top-30|work=womens.afl|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> She was selected in ''womens.afl''{{'}}s Team of the Week in rounds 1,<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round one|url=https://womens.afl/news/43976/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-one|work=womens.afl|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> 3<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round three|url=https://womens.afl/news/46374/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-three|work=womens.afl|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> and 6,<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round six|url=https://womens.afl/news/49340/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-six|work=womens.afl|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and tied with {{AFLW NM}}'s [[Jasmine Garner]] and {{AFLW Mel}}'s [[Karen Paxman]] as ''womens.afl''{{'}}s player of the year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Three-way tie for player of the year|url=https://womens.afl/news/49368/three-way-tie-for-player-of-the-year|work=womens.afl|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Prespakis was selected in the initial 40-woman squad for the [[2020 AFL Women's All-Australian team]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=REVEALED: Magpies lead the way in All-Australian squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50080/revealed-magpies-lead-the-way-in-all-australian-squad|work=womens.afl|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AFLW statement: 2020 AFLW All-Australian Squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50079/aflw-statement-2020-aflw-all-australian-squad|work=womens.afl|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Negrepontis|first=Nic|title=Official 2020 AFLW All-Australian squad revealed|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2020/04/03/official-2020-aflw-all-australian-squad-revealed/|work=[[1116 SEN|SEN]]|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> and was also selected as vice-captain in the [[AFL Players Association]]'s inaugural AFL Women's 22under22 team,<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=AFLPA award winners revealed: MVP, best captain, more|url=https://womens.afl/news/50111/aflpa-award-winners-revealed-mvp-best-captain-more|work=womens.afl|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Negrepontis|first=Nic|title=2020 AFLW 22 under 22 team revealed|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2020/04/20/2020-aflw-22-under-22-team-revealed/|work=[[1116 SEN|SEN]]|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AFLW 22under22 side revealed|url=http://www.aflplayers.com.au/article/aflw-22under22-side-revealed/|work=aflplayers.com.au|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> having earlier been selected in the retrospective 2017\u20132019 team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Crows dominate inaugural 22under22 squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50053/crows-dominate-inaugural-22under22-squad|work=womens.afl|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> She went on to win her second Carlton best and fairest award, after coming second in voting for the AFLW Players' most valuable player award for that season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=Young Blue makes it two from two B&F wins|url=https://womens.afl/news/50116/young-blue-makes-it-two-from-two-b-f-wins|work=womens.afl|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n:''Statistics are correct to the end of the 2020 season''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madison Prespakis|url=https://australianfootball.com/players/playerseason/Madison%2BPrespakis/20386|work=Australian Football|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Australian rules football statistics legend}}\n{{AFLW player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background:#EAEAEA\"\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2019 AFL Women's season|2019]]\n| {{AFLW Car}}\n| 4 || 9 || 7 || 3 || 113 || 59 || 172 || 17 || 27 || 0.8 || 0.3 || 12.6 || 6.6 || 19.1 || 1.9 || 3.0 || 5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2020 AFL Women's season|2020]]\n| {{AFLW Car}}\n| 4 || 7 || 3 || 3 || 88 || 61 || 149 || 19 || 21 || 0.4 || 0.4 || 12.6 || 8.7 || 21.3 || 2.7 || 3.0 || \n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=3 | Career\n! 16\n! 10\n! 4\n! 201\n! 120\n! 321\n! 36\n! 48\n! 0.6\n! 0.3\n! 12.6\n! 7.5\n! 20.1\n! 2.3\n! 3.0\n! 5\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2018, Prespakis began dating [[Serene Watson]], who began playing for {{AFLW GC}} in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Montesano|first=Julia|title=They\u2019re the AFLW\u2019s newest power couple. The problem is they\u2019re on rival teams|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/afl-womens-2020-madison-prespakis-serene-watson-couple-carlton-aflw-gold-coast-suns-aflw-aflw-draft/news-story/2b35ad98ec0114fed34e94aac9d8a830|work=[[Fox Sports (Australian TV network)|Fox Sports]]|date=25 October 2019|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bilton|first=Dean|title=The Maddy Prespakis Era has arrived, and that's great news for AFLW|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-14/the-maddy-prespakis-era-has-arrived-good-news-for-aflw/11964922|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and achievements==\n'''Individual'''\n* '''[[AFL Women's All-Australian team]]''': [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team|2019]]\n* '''2\u00d7 [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]]''': 2019, 2020\n* '''[[AFL Women's Rising Star]]''': [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star|2019]]\n* '''AFLW Players' best first-year player''': 2019\n* '''AFL Women's 22under22 team''': 2020 (vc)\n* '''AFL Women's 2017\u20132019 22under22 team'''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Carlplayer|2051/madison-prespakis}}\n* {{AustralianFootball|ref=Madison%2BPrespakis/20386}}\n* {{Instagram|id=maddyprespakis}}\n\n{{Carlton AFL Women's player squad}}\n{{2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team}}\n{{Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)}}\n{{AFL Women's Rising Star winners}}\n{{AFLW Players' best first-year player award}}\n{{2018 AFL Women's draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prespakis, Madison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian players of Australian rules football]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Calder Cannons players]]\n[[Category:Carlton Football Club (AFLW) players]]\n[[Category:Melbourne University Football Club (VFLW) players]]\n[[Category:Calder Cannons players (NAB League Girls)]]\n[[Category:Lesbian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT players of Australian rules football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Madison Prespakis\n| image = Madison Prespakis 2019.2.jpg\n| caption = Prespakis playing for Carlton's VFLW team in 2019\n| fullname = Madison Prespakis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|2000|11|02|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| originalteam = {{VFLW MU}} ([[VFL Women's|VFLW]])\n| draftpick  = No. 3, [[2018 AFL Women's draft#Draft|2018 national draft]]\n| debutdate = Round 1, 2019\n| debutteam = {{AFLW Car}}\n| debutopponent = {{AFLW NM}}\n| debutstadium = [[North Hobart Oval]]\n| height = 164&nbsp;cm\n| position = [[Australian rules football positions#Midfield|Midfielder]]\n| currentclub = {{AFLW Car}}\n| guernsey = 4\n| years1 = 2019\u2013\n| club1 = {{AFLW Car}}\n| games_goals1 = 16 (10)\n| statsend = the 2020 season\n| careerhighlights =\n* [[AFL Women's All-Australian team]]: [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team|2019]]\n* 2\u00d7 [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]]: 2019, 2020\n* [[AFL Women's Rising Star]]: [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star|2019]]\n* AFLW Players' best first-year player: 2019\n}}\n\n'''Madison Prespakis''' (born 2 November 2000) is an [[Australian rules football]]er playing for [[Carlton Football Club#AFL Women's team|Carlton Football Club]] in the [[AFL Women's]] (AFLW). A midfielder who won multiple accolades at junior level and played in the [[VFL Women's]] (VFLW) as a teenager, Prespakis won the [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star]] award and [[AFL Women's All-Australian team|AFL Women's All-Australian]] selection in 2019, and is a dual [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]] winner.\n\n== Early life ==\nPrespakis is the daughter of Damien and Jody.<ref name='Black AFL.com.au'>{{cite news |last1=Black |first1=Sarah |title=AFLW: From Auskick to likely top-three pick |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2018-10-21/aflw-from-auskick-to-likely-top-three-pick |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=21 October 2018}}</ref><ref name='McGowan AFL.com.au'>{{cite news |last1=McGowan |first1=Marc |title=AFLW: New Blue happy to be close to home |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2018-10-23/aflw-new-blue-happy-to-be-close-to-home |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> Her mother is an [[Indigenous Australian]] from the [[Djadjawurrung]] tribe.<ref name='McGowan AFL.com.au/> Prespakis has three siblings: twin sister Annalea, Georgie, and Jimmy.<ref name='Black AFL.com.au'/> She attended [[Gisborne Secondary College]] and supported {{AFL Ess}} growing up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Barry |title=Sunbury teen Maddy inspired to join AFLW ranks |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/north-west/sunbury-teen-maddy-inspired-to-join-aflw-ranks/news-story/780b869a1230e2bb4407a150ffe148fa |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=Sunbury Leader |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 June 2017}}</ref>\nPrespakis began playing football at four years old through the [[Auskick]] program in [[Romsey, Victoria|Romsey]], north-west of [[Melbourne]]. She played in boys' teams at first, before representing the under-15 [[Sunbury Football Netball Club|Sunbury]] girls side.<ref name='canberra times'>{{cite news |last1=Fowler |first1=Michael |title=Debut 15 years in the making for AFLW's new breed of role model |url=https://www.canberratimes.com.au/sport/afl/debut-15-years-in-the-making-for-aflw-s-new-breed-of-role-model-20190207-p50w8t.html?ref=rss |accessdate=25 February 2019 |work=[[The Canberra Times]] |publisher=[[Fairfax Media]] |date=9 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Prespakis played in the premiership-winning [[Calder Cannons]] side in the [[NAB League#NAB League Girls|TAC Cup Girls]].<ref name='AFL Vic 2017'>{{cite news |title=Calder TAC Cup Premiers |url=https://aflvic.com.au/calder-tac-cup-girls-premiers/ |accessdate=26 February 2019 |work=aflvic.com.au |publisher=AFL Victoria |date=10 May 2017}}</ref> She was named in the league's team of the year<ref name='draft watch'/> and placed second in the league's [[best and fairest]] with 20 votes.<ref name='AFL Vic 2017'/> She competed at the [[2017 AFL Women's Under 18 Championships]] for Vic Metro and was named in the All-Australian squad.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Black |first1=Sarah |title=AFLW U18 All Australian squad named |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-07-18/aflw-u18-all-australian-squad-named |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=18 July 2017}}</ref> In October, Prespakis was named in the 2018 AFLW Academy squad as one of twenty-nine seventeen-year-old prospects. As part of this squad, she trained with the {{AFLW WB}} and {{AFLW Col}} over the following months.<ref>{{cite news |title=AFLW: 2018 Academy prospects revealed |url=https://www.afl.com.au/news/2017-10-25/aflw-2018-academy-prospects-revealed |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=AFL.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=25 October 2017}}</ref><ref name='canberra times'/>\n\nIn 2018, Prespakis became captain of the Calder Cannons<ref name='draft watch'>{{cite news |title=AFLW Draft Watch: Madison Prespakis |url=https://taccup.com.au/aflw-draft-watch-madison-prespakis/ |accessdate=15 February 2019 |work=taccup.com.au |publisher=AFL Victoria |date=15 October 2018}}</ref> and won their best and fairest award with 113 out of a possible 120 votes.<ref name='pick 3'>{{cite news |last1=Balales |first1=Danielle |title=Pick 3: Madison Prespakis |url=https://www.carltonfc.com.au/news/2018-10-23/pick-3-madison-prespakis |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=carltonfc.com.au |publisher=[[Telstra Media]] |date=23 October 2018}}</ref> She was again named in the TAC Cup Girls Team of the Year and tied with [[Nina Morrison]] for the league best and fairest. She again competed at the [[2018 AFL Women's Under 18 Championships]]; she shared the competition's most valuable player award with Morrison on 16 votes apiece, won Vic Metro's most valuable player award and was named in the All-Australian side.<ref name='fox exhibition'>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft: Potential top picks star in U18 All-Stars exhibition match |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/aflw-draft-potential-top-picks-star-in-u18-allstars-exhibition-match/news-story/57d9a17516a0d749f650acf48fcc9d65 |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=1 September 2018}}</ref><ref name='fox TAC Cup'/> She played in an [[exhibition game]] for Victoria, acting as a curtain raiser for the [[E. J. Whitten Legends Game]]. Prespakis amassed 21 disposals in Victoria's win, the most of any player.<ref name='fox exhibition'/> Aside from under-18 competitions, she also played six matches for {{VFLW MU}} in the [[VFL Women's]] (VFLW).<ref name='fox TAC Cup'>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft 2018: Future stars Nina Morrison and Madison Prespakis share in TAC Cup\u2019s top award |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/aflw-draft-2018-future-stars-nina-morrison-and-madison-prespakis-share-in-tac-cups-top-award/news-story/a0b4249c370a614db0609caec49bc89e |accessdate=27 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=4 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nAhead of the [[2018 AFL Women's draft]], Prespakis was widely predicted to be taken with one of the first selections.<ref name=\"Black AFL.com.au\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Balmer |first1=Matt |title=AFLW Draft 2018: Full first-round mock draft for AFL women's draft |url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/aflw-draft-2018-full-firstround-mock-draft-for-afl-womens-draft/news-story/44fa870081e188854ea3ee01b03e0374 |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=[[Fox Sports (Australia)|Fox Sports]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 October 2018}}</ref> Prospective draftees were required to nominate a state or region they wished to play in; Prespakis selected the Melbourne metropolitan area, citing a wish to remain home with her family. This prevented {{AFLW Gee}} from recruiting her with pick one or two and allowed Carlton the opportunity to select her with pick three.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sewell |first1=Eliza |title=Carlton in box seat to land talented midfielder Madison Prespakis in AFLW draft |url=https://www.heraldsun.com.au/sport/afl/aflw/carlton-in-box-seat-to-land-talented-midfielder-madison-prespakis-in-aflw-draft/news-story/3b44de04df50799d5132d7216de95551 |accessdate=28 February 2019 |work=[[Herald Sun]] |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=2 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==AFL Women's career==\n[[File:Madison Prespakis 23.03.19 (cropped).jpg|thumb|175px|Prespakis playing for Carlton in 2019]]\nCarlton recruited Prespakis with their first selection and third overall in the 2018 AFL Women's draft.<ref name='pick 3'/> She made her AFL Women's debut in the opening round of the 2019 season against {{AFLW NM}} at [[North Hobart Oval]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Warren|first=Stu|title=Match report: Roos thrash Blues on memorable debut|url=https://womens.afl/news/15891/match-report-roos-thrash-blues-on-memorable-debut|work=womens.afl|date=3 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> The following round, she was nominated for the [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star]] award after kicking one goal and amassing 20 disposals, seven clearances and nine contested possessions against {{AFLW Ade}}.<ref>{{cite news|last=Olsson-Young|first=Marni|title=Blue, Docker take out round-two Rising Star nominations|url=https://womens.afl/news/16388/blue-docker-take-out-round-two-rising-star-nominations|work=womens.afl|date=12 February 2019|accessdate=15 February 2019}}</ref> Prespakis went on to play in the [[2019 AFL Women's Grand Final]] loss to Adelaide in front of a record AFL Women's crowd, and was among Carlton's best players.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gaskin|first=Lee|title=Crows soar to flag in front of record crowd, but injury hits superstar|url=https://womens.afl/news/17614/crows-soar-to-flag-in-front-of-record-crowd-but-injury-hits-superstar|work=womens.afl|date=31 March 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> Following a debut season in which she averaged 19 disposals and kicked seven goals across nine games,<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=How will Blues replace ex-skipper after shock move to arch rivals?|url=https://womens.afl/news/40184/how-will-blues-replace-ex-skipper-after-shock-move-to-arch-rivals-|work=womens.afl|date=28 December 2019|accessdate=28 December 2019}}</ref> Prespakis won the 2019 AFL Women's Rising Star award with 49 votes and was named in the [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Navaratnam|first=Dinny|title=Five Crows, four Roos headline All Australian team|url=https://womens.afl/news/17673/five-crows-four-roos-headline-all-australian-team|work=womens.afl|date=2 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> She also won the AFLW Players' best first-year player award<ref>{{cite news|last1=Black|first1=Sarah|author2=[[Australian Associated Press]]|title=Superstar Crow clinches second MVP award|url=https://womens.afl/news/17658/superstar-crow-clinches-second-mvp-award|work=womens.afl|date=1 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> and tied for the [[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]] award with captain [[Brianna Davey]], capping off a memorable first season.<ref>{{cite news|title=First-year Blue ties with skipper to win best and fairest|url=https://womens.afl/news/17794/first-year-blue-ties-with-skipper-to-win-best-and-fairest|work=womens.afl|date=12 April 2019|accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nLeading into the 2020 season, ''womens.afl'' journalist Sarah Black named Prespakis at no. 23 on her list of the top 30 players in the AFLW.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Sarah Black's top 30: Young Blue bolts into No.23|url=https://womens.afl/news/40286/sarah-black-s-top-30|work=womens.afl|date=15 January 2020|accessdate=18 January 2020}}</ref> She was selected in ''womens.afl''{{'}}s Team of the Week in rounds 1,<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round one|url=https://womens.afl/news/43976/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-one|work=womens.afl|date=11 February 2020|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref> 3<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round three|url=https://womens.afl/news/46374/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-three|work=womens.afl|date=25 February 2020|accessdate=25 February 2020}}</ref> and 6,<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=AFLW Team of the Week, round six|url=https://womens.afl/news/49340/aflw-team-of-the-week-round-six|work=womens.afl|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> and tied with {{AFLW NM}}'s [[Jasmine Garner]] and {{AFLW Mel}}'s [[Karen Paxman]] as ''womens.afl''{{'}}s player of the year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Three-way tie for player of the year|url=https://womens.afl/news/49368/three-way-tie-for-player-of-the-year|work=womens.afl|date=21 March 2020|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> Prespakis was selected in the initial 40-woman squad for the [[2020 AFL Women's All-Australian team]],<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=REVEALED: Magpies lead the way in All-Australian squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50080/revealed-magpies-lead-the-way-in-all-australian-squad|work=womens.afl|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AFLW statement: 2020 AFLW All-Australian Squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50079/aflw-statement-2020-aflw-all-australian-squad|work=womens.afl|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Negrepontis|first=Nic|title=Official 2020 AFLW All-Australian squad revealed|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2020/04/03/official-2020-aflw-all-australian-squad-revealed/|work=[[1116 SEN|SEN]]|date=3 April 2020|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> and was also selected as vice-captain in the [[AFL Players Association]]'s inaugural AFL Women's 22under22 team,<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=AFLPA award winners revealed: MVP, best captain, more|url=https://womens.afl/news/50111/aflpa-award-winners-revealed-mvp-best-captain-more|work=womens.afl|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Negrepontis|first=Nic|title=2020 AFLW 22 under 22 team revealed|url=https://www.sen.com.au/news/2020/04/20/2020-aflw-22-under-22-team-revealed/|work=[[1116 SEN|SEN]]|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AFLW 22under22 side revealed|url=http://www.aflplayers.com.au/article/aflw-22under22-side-revealed/|work=aflplayers.com.au|date=20 April 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> having earlier been selected in the retrospective 2017\u20132019 team.<ref>{{cite news|last=Black|first=Sarah|title=Crows dominate inaugural 22under22 squad|url=https://womens.afl/news/50053/crows-dominate-inaugural-22under22-squad|work=womens.afl|date=26 March 2020|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> She went on to win her second Carlton best and fairest award, after coming second in voting for the AFLW Players' most valuable player award for that season.<ref>{{cite news|last=Beveridge|first=Riley|title=Young Blue makes it two from two B&F wins|url=https://womens.afl/news/50116/young-blue-makes-it-two-from-two-b-f-wins|work=womens.afl|date=23 April 2020|accessdate=23 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n:''Statistics are correct to the end of the 2020 season''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madison Prespakis|url=https://australianfootball.com/players/playerseason/Madison%2BPrespakis/20386|work=Australian Football|accessdate=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Australian rules football statistics legend}}\n{{AFLW player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background:#EAEAEA\"\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2019 AFL Women's season|2019]]\n| {{AFLW Car}}\n| 4 || 9 || 7 || 3 || 113 || 59 || 172 || 17 || 27 || 0.8 || 0.3 || 12.6 || 6.6 || 19.1 || 1.9 || 3.0 || 5\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" text-align:center | [[2020 AFL Women's season|2020]]\n| {{AFLW Car}}\n| 4 || 7 || 3 || 3 || 88 || 61 || 149 || 19 || 21 || 0.4 || 0.4 || 12.6 || 8.7 || 21.3 || 2.7 || 3.0 || \n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=3 | Career\n! 16\n! 10\n! 4\n! 201\n! 120\n! 321\n! 36\n! 48\n! 0.6\n! 0.3\n! 12.6\n! 7.5\n! 20.1\n! 2.3\n! 3.0\n! 5\n|}\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2018, Prespakis began dating [[Serene Watson]], who began playing for {{AFLW GC}} in 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last=Montesano|first=Julia|title=They\u2019re the AFLW\u2019s newest power couple. The problem is they\u2019re on rival teams|url=https://www.foxsports.com.au/afl/womens-afl/afl-womens-2020-madison-prespakis-serene-watson-couple-carlton-aflw-gold-coast-suns-aflw-aflw-draft/news-story/2b35ad98ec0114fed34e94aac9d8a830|work=[[Fox Sports (Australian TV network)|Fox Sports]]|date=25 October 2019|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Bilton|first=Dean|title=The Maddy Prespakis Era has arrived, and that's great news for AFLW|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2020-02-14/the-maddy-prespakis-era-has-arrived-good-news-for-aflw/11964922|work=[[ABC News (Australia)]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and achievements==\n'''Individual'''\n* '''[[AFL Women's All-Australian team]]''': [[2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team|2019]]\n* '''[[Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)|Carlton best and fairest]]''': 2019\n* '''[[AFL Women's Rising Star]]''': [[2019 AFL Women's Rising Star|2019]]\n* '''AFLW Players' best first-year player''': 2019\n* '''AFL Women's 22under22 team''': 2020 (vc)\n* '''AFL Women's 2017\u20132019 22under22 team'''\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Carlplayer|2051/madison-prespakis}}\n* {{AustralianFootball|ref=Madison%2BPrespakis/20386}}\n* {{Instagram|id=maddyprespakis}}\n\n{{Carlton AFL Women's player squad}}\n{{2019 AFL Women's All-Australian team}}\n{{Carlton best and fairest (AFL Women's)}}\n{{AFL Women's Rising Star winners}}\n{{AFLW Players' best first-year player award}}\n{{2018 AFL Women's draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Prespakis, Madison}}\n[[Category:2000 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indigenous Australian players of Australian rules football]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Calder Cannons players]]\n[[Category:Carlton Football Club (AFLW) players]]\n[[Category:Melbourne University Football Club (VFLW) players]]\n[[Category:Calder Cannons players (NAB League Girls)]]\n[[Category:Lesbian sportswomen]]\n[[Category:LGBT sportspeople from Australia]]\n[[Category:LGBT players of Australian rules football]]\n", "name_user": "4TheWynne", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHonours and achievements", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Madison_Prespakis"}
{"title_page": "Pak Sung-won", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_date=November 1946\n|death_date=\n|nationality=North Korean\n|occupation=Military officer, politician\n|birth_place=\n|education = \n|party= [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|nationality = [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|citizenship = [[Citizenship in North Korea|North Korean]]\n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea|1948}}\n|branch       = {{armed forces|North Korea}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Kim Il-sung Military University]]\n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  [[image:General of the Army rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Daejang|General]]\n}}\n'''Park Sung-won ({{lang-ko|\ubc15\uc2b9\uc6d0}})''' (born November 1946) is a former military officer and politician of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea ([[North Korea]]) who was a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. He served as delegate to the [[2009 North Korean parlaimentary election|12th convocation]] of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. In 2015 he defected.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in November 1946. He graduated from Kim Il-Sung Military University, and in April 1992, became the rank of general of the Korean People's Army. He served as Deputy Chief of Staff for the People's Army General Staff. In 1998, he served as the 10th delegate to the Supreme People's Assembly. It is the 12th delegate since April 2009. During the first inter-Korean defense ministers' meeting in September 2000, he served as Deputy Chairman of the North Korean delegation, and in April 2002, the rank of the People's Army was granted.<ref>[http://unibook.unikorea.go.kr/?sub_num=54&state=view&idx=360&sty=T&ste=%B9%DA%BD%C2%BF%F8]</ref> In September 2010, he was elected to the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea.\n\nHe participated in the funeral committes which organized the funerals of Choi Kwang in 1997, [[Yon Hyong-muk]] in 2005, [[Jo Myong-rok]] in 2010, and Kim Jong-il [[Death and Funeral of Kim Jong-il|following his death]] in 2011. After leaving North Korea in April 2015, they filed for asylum with the [[Embassy of South Korea, Moscow|South Korean Embassy in Moscow]].<ref>http://kor.theasian.asia/archives/140451</ref><ref>http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/07/04/0200000000AKR20150704052000014.HTML?input=1195m</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{North Korean generals}}\n\n[[Category:North Korean defectors]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n[[ko:\ubc15\uc2b9\uc6d0 (1946\ub144)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|birth_date=November 1946\n|death_date=\n|nationality=North Korean\n|occupation=Military officer, politician\n|birth_place=\n|education = \n|party= [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n|nationality = [[Korean people|Korean]]\n|citizenship = [[Citizenship in North Korea|North Korean]]\n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea|1948}}\n|branch       = {{armed forces|North Korea}}\n|alma_mater   = [[Kim Il-sung Military University]]\n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  [[image:General rank insignia (North Korea).svg|25px]] [[Daejang|General]]\n}}\n'''Park Sung-won ({{lang-ko|\ubc15\uc2b9\uc6d0}})''' (born November 1946) is a former military officer and politician of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea ([[North Korea]]) who was a member of the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]. He served as delegate to the [[2009 North Korean parlaimentary election|12th convocation]] of the [[Supreme People's Assembly]]. In 2015 he defected.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in November 1946. He graduated from Kim Il-Sung Military University, and in April 1992, became the rank of general of the Korean People's Army. He served as Deputy Chief of Staff for the People's Army General Staff. In 1998, he served as the 10th delegate to the Supreme People's Assembly. It is the 12th delegate since April 2009. During the first inter-Korean defense ministers' meeting in September 2000, he served as Deputy Chairman of the North Korean delegation, and in April 2002, the rank of the People's Army was granted.<ref>[http://unibook.unikorea.go.kr/?sub_num=54&state=view&idx=360&sty=T&ste=%B9%DA%BD%C2%BF%F8]</ref> In September 2010, he was elected to the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea.\n\nHe participated in the funeral committes which organized the funerals of Choi Kwang in 1997, [[Yon Hyong-muk]] in 2005, [[Jo Myong-rok]] in 2010, and Kim Jong-il [[Death and Funeral of Kim Jong-il|following his death]] in 2011. After leaving North Korea in April 2015, they filed for asylum with the [[Embassy of South Korea, Moscow|South Korean Embassy in Moscow]].<ref>http://kor.theasian.asia/archives/140451</ref><ref>http://www.yonhapnews.co.kr/bulletin/2015/07/04/0200000000AKR20150704052000014.HTML?input=1195m</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{North Korean generals}}\n\n[[Category:North Korean defectors]]\n[[Category:North Korean generals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Supreme People's Assembly]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n[[ko:\ubc15\uc2b9\uc6d0 (1946\ub144)]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pak_Sung-won"}
{"title_page": "Religious Zionism", "text_new": "{{short description|Ideology that combines Zionism and Orthodox Judaism}}\n[[File:Kippot.jpg|thumb|Crocheted [[kippot]]]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 7273 \u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e6\u05d9quot;\u05d1 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionist pioneers found Kibbutz [[Ein HaNatziv]], 1946]]\n\n'''Religious Zionism''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b4\u05d9\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05e0\u05d5\u05bc\u05ea \u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, [[Romanization of Hebrew|translit.]] ''Tziyonut Datit'', or {{Hebrew|\u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05b0\u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9}} ''Dati Leumi'' \"National Religious\", or {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4 \u05e1\u05b0\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d2\u05b8\u05d4}} ''Kippah seruga'', literally, \"knitted skullcap\") is an ideology that combines [[Zionism]] and [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\nBefore the establishment of [[Israel|the State of Israel]], Religious Zionists were mainly observant Jews who supported Zionist efforts to build a [[Jewish state]] in the [[Land of Israel]].\n\nAfter the [[Six-Day War]], and the capture of the [[West Bank]], a territory referred to in Jewish terms as [[Judea and Samaria]], right-wing components of the Religious Zionist movement integrated nationalist revindication{{explain|This term is not defined here, nor under the Ideology heading, and has no page or definition at the encyclopedia|date=July 2018}}, and evolved into [[Neo-Zionism]]. Their ideology revolves around three pillars: the Land of Israel, the People of Israel, and the Torah of Israel.<ref>[[Adriana Kemp]], ''Israelis in Conflict: Hegemonies, Identities, and Challenges'', Sussex Academic Press, 2004, pp.314\u2013315.</ref>\n\nThe [[Hardal]] (\u200e \u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d0\u05d5\u05de\u05d9 \u1e24aredi Le'umi, lit.\u2009\"Nationalist [[Haredi]]\") are a sub-community; stricter in observance, and more \"statist\" in their politics.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Abraham Isaac Kook 1924.jpg|thumb|[[Abraham Isaac Kook]], 1924]]\n\nIn 1862, German Orthodox [[Rabbi]] [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]] published his tractate ''Derishat Zion'', positing that the salvation of the Jews, promised by the [[Nevi'im|Prophets]], can come about only by self-help.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=56&letter=K Zvi Hirsch Kalischer] (Jewish Encyclopedia)</ref> Rabbi [[Moshe Shmuel Glasner]] was another prominent rabbi who supported Zionism. The main ideologue of modern Religious Zionism was Rabbi [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], who justified Zionism according to [[Halakha|Jewish law]], and urged young religious Jews to support efforts to settle the land, and the secular [[Labour Zionist]]s to give more consideration to Judaism. Kook saw Zionism as a part of a divine scheme which would result in the resettlement of the Jewish people in its homeland. This would bring salvation (\"Geula\") to Jews, and then to the entire world. After world harmony is achieved by the refoundation of the Jewish homeland, the [[Messiah]] will come. Although this has not yet happened, Kook emphasized that it would take time, and that the ultimate redemption happens in stages, often not apparent while happening. In 1924, when Kook became the [[Ashkenazi]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], he tried to reconcile Zionism with [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Jerusalem Day.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionists celebrating [[Jerusalem Day]]]]\nReligious Zionists believe that \"[[Eretz Israel|Eretz Yisrael]]\" (the Land of Israel) was promised to the ancient [[Israelites]] by [[God in Judaism|God]].  Furthermore, modern Jews have the obligation to possess and defend the land in ways that comport with the [[Torah]]'s high standards of justice.<ref>Novak, David.  [https://mosaicmagazine.com/response/politics-current-affairs/2020/01/what-unites-people-of-faith-across-religions-and-divides-them-from-others/ \"What Unites People of Faith across Religions, and Divides Them from Others.\"] ''Mosaic''.  23 January 2020.  23 January 2020.</ref> To generations of [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora Jews]], [[Jerusalem]] has been a symbol of the [[Holy Land]] and of their return to it, as promised by God in numerous [[Bible|Biblical prophecies]]. Despite this, many Jews did not embrace Zionism before the 1930s, and certain religious groups opposed it then, as some groups still do now, on the grounds that an attempt to re-establish Jewish rule in Israel by [[human agency]] was blasphemous. Hastening salvation and the coming of the Messiah was considered religiously forbidden, and Zionism was seen as a sign of disbelief in God's power, and therefore, a rebellion against God. Rabbi Kook developed a [[theology|theological]] answer to that claim, which gave Zionism a religious legitimation: \"Zionism was not merely a political movement by secular Jews. It was actually a tool of [[God]] to promote His divine scheme, and to initiate the return of the Jews to their homeland \u2013 the land He promised to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]]. God wants the [[children of Israel]] to return to their home in order to establish a Jewish sovereign state in which Jews could live according to the laws of [[Torah]] and [[Halakha]], and commit the [[Mitzvah|Mitzvot]] of Eretz Israel (these are religious commandments which can be performed only in the [[Land of Israel]]). Moreover, to cultivate the Land of Israel was a Mitzvah by itself, and it should be carried out. Therefore, settling [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is an obligation of the religious Jews, and helping Zionism is actually following God's will.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Torat Eretz Yisrael|first=David|last=Samson|author2=Tzvi Fishman |publisher=Torat Eretz Yisrael Publications|location=Jerusalem |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nReligious Jews also disapproved of the Zionists because many were secular Jews or [[atheist]]s, taking their cue from [[Marxism]]. [[Labour Zionism|Socialist Zionism]] envisaged the movement as a tool for building an advanced [[socialist]] society in the land of Israel, while solving the problem of [[antisemitism]]. The early [[kibbutz]] was a communal settlement that focused on national goals, unencumbered by religion and precepts of Jewish law such as [[kashrut]]. Socialist Zionists were one of the results of a long process of modernization within the Jewish communities of Europe, known as the [[Haskalah]], or Jewish Enlightenment. Rabbi Kook's answer was as follows:\n\n:''Secular Zionists may think they do it for political, national, or socialist reasons, but in fact \u2013 the actual reason for them coming to resettle in [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is a religious Jewish spark (\"Nitzotz\") in their [[soul]], planted by God. Without their knowledge, they are contributing to the divine scheme and actually committing a great [[Mitzvah]].''\n\n:''The role of religious Zionists is to help them to establish a Jewish state and turn the religious spark in them into a great light. They should show them that the real source of Zionism and the longed-for Zion is [[Judaism]] and teach them [[Torah]] with love and kindness. In the end, they will understand that the laws of [[Torah]] are the key to true [[harmony]] and a [[socialist]] state (not in the [[Marxist]] [[Socialist mode of production|meaning]]) that will be a light for the [[goyim|nations]] and bring salvation to the world.''\n\n[[Shlomo Avineri]] explained the last part of Kook's answer: \"... and the end of those pioneers, who scout into the blindness of secularism and atheism, but the treasured light inside them leads them into the path of salvation \u2013 their end is that from doing Mitzva without purpose, they will do Mitzva with a purpose.\" (page 222, <sup>[[Religious Zionist Movement#References|1]]</sup>)\n\n== Organizations ==\n[[File:Bnei akiva logo.jpg|thumb|100px|left|[[Bnei Akiva]] youth movement, combining Torah and work]]\n\nThe first rabbis to support Zionism were [[Judah Alkalai|Yehuda Shlomo Alkalai]] and [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]. They argued that the change in the status of [[Western Europe]]'s Jews following [[Jewish emancipation|emancipation]] was the first step toward redemption (\u05d2\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4), and that, therefore, one must hasten the messianic salvation by a natural salvation \u2013 whose main pillars are the [[Kibbutz Galuyot]] (\"Gathering of the Exiles\"), the return to Eretz Israel, agricultural work (\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05ea \u05d0\u05d3\u05de\u05d4), and the revival of the everyday use of the [[Hebrew language]].\n\nThe [[Mizrachi (Religious Zionism)|Mizrachi]] organization was established in 1902 in [[Vilna]] at a world conference of Religious Zionists. It operates a [[Zionist youth movement|youth movement]], [[Bnei Akiva]], which was founded in 1929. Mizrachi believes that the [[Torah]] should be at the centre of [[Zionism]], a sentiment expressed in the Mizrachi Zionist slogan ''Am Yisrael B'Eretz Yisrael al pi Torat Yisrael'' (\"The people of Israel in the land of Israel according to the Torah of Israel\"). It also sees Jewish nationalism as a tool for achieving religious objectives. Mizrachi was the first official Religious Zionist party. It also built a network of religious schools that exist to this day.\n\nIn 1937-1948, the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]] established three settlement blocs of three kibbutzim each. The first was in the [[Beit Shean]] Valley, the second was in the [[Hebron]] mountains south of [[Bethlehem]] (known as [[Gush Etzion]]), and the third was in the western [[Negev]]. Kibbutz [[Yavne]] was founded in the center of the country as the core of a fourth bloc that came into being after the establishment of the state.<ref>\"Settlement clustering on a socio-cultural basis: The bloc settlement policy of the Religious Kibbutz Movement in Palestine,\" Yossi Katz, ''Journal of Rural Studies'', vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 161\u2013171, 1995</ref>\n\n== Political parties ==\nThe [[Labor Movement]] wing of Religious Zionism, founded in 1921 under the Zionist slogan \"Torah va'Avodah\" (Torah and Labor), was called [[Hapoel HaMizrachi]]. It represented religiously traditional [[Labour Zionism|Labour Zionists]], both in Europe and in the Land of Israel, where it represented religious Jews in the [[Histadrut]]. In 1956, Mizrachi, Hapoel HaMizrachi, and other religious Zionists formed the [[National Religious Party]] to advance the rights of religious Zionist Jews in Israel. Other parties and groups affiliated with religious Zionism are [[Gush Emunim]], [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]], and [[Meimad]]. [[Kahanism]], a radical branch of religious Zionism, was founded by Rabbi [[Meir Kahane]], whose party, [[Kach and Kahane Chai|Kach]], was eventually banned for [[racism]]. Today, [[Otzma Yehudit]] is the leading wing of this school of thought.\n\n== Educational institutions ==\n:''See: [[Yeshiva #Israel]]; [[:Category:Religious Zionist yeshivot]]; [[List of Midrashot]].''\n[[File:Mercaz HaRav01.JPG|thumb|[[Mercaz Harav]], Jerusalem]]\nThe flagship religious institution of the Religious Zionist movement is the [[yeshiva]] founded by Rabbi Abraham Isaac Kook in 1924, called in his honor \"[[Mercaz haRav]]\" (lit., the Rabbi's center). \nOther Religious Zionist yeshivot include [[Ateret Cohanim]], [[Beit El yeshiva]] and Yeshivat [[Or Etzion]], founded by Rav [[Haim Druckman]], a foremost disciple of Rabbi [[Tzvi Yehuda Kook]].\n\nThere are also approximately 90 ''[[Hesder]]'' yeshivot, allowing students to continue [[Torah study]] during their National Service (see [[#Military_service|below]]).\nThe first was [[Yeshivat Kerem B'Yavneh]], established in 1954; the largest is the [[Hesder Yeshiva of Sderot]] with over 800 students.\nOthers well known include [[Machon Meir|Yeshivat Machon Meir]], [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], [[Yeshivat HaKotel]], [[Yeshivat Birkat Moshe]] in [[Maale Adumim]], [[Yeshiva Har Bracha|Yeshivat Har Bracha]] and Yeshivat Har Hamor.  \n\nThese institutions usually offer a [[kollel]] for ''[[Semikha]]'', or Rabbinic ordination. Students generally prepare for the ''Semikha'' test of the [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel]]; often for that of the [[posek]] R. [[Zalman Nechemia Goldberg]].\nTraining as a [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]] in this community is usually through [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d0\u05dc|''Machon Ariel'']] (''[[Machon Harry Fischel]]''), also founded by Rav Kook, or [[:he:\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5_\u05d7\u05de\u05d3\u05d4_(\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dc) |''Kollel Eretz Hemda'']].\n\nWomen study in institutions known as ''Midrashot'' (sing. [[Midrasha]]) - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]]. Some also offer degree studies (and may then be known as a ''machon'').\n[[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] trains women as [[Yoetzet Halacha|Yoatzot Halacha]]; see also [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] and [[Matan Women's Institute for Torah Studies|Matan]], which similarly offer Talmud focused learning to women.\n\nHigh school students study at [[Education_in_Israel#Educational_tracks|''Mamlachti dati'']] schools, often associated with ''[[Bnei Akiva]]''. The first of these was at [[Kfar Haroeh]] established by [[Moshe-Zvi Neria]]. A girls' high school is referred to as an ''[[Ulpana]]''.\nFor degree studies, many attend [[Bar Ilan University]], which allows students to combine Yeshiva studies with university study; \n[[Jerusalem College of Technology]] similarly (which also offers a Haredi track).\nThere are also [[List_of_Israeli_universities_and_colleges#Colleges|several colleges of education]] associated with Hesder and the ''Midrashot'', such as [[Herzog College]] and the [[Lifshitz College of Education]]. These often allow specializations in [[Tanach]] and ''Machshava'' ([[Jewish thought]]).\n\nSome institutions are aligned with the ''Hardal'' community, with an ideology that is somewhat more \"statist\".\nThe leading Yeshiva here is [[Har Hamor]]; [[Hardal#Schools|several high schools]] also operate.\n\n== Politics ==\nMost Religious Zionists embrace [[right-wing]] politics, especially the religious right-wing [[Jewish Home]] party, but also support the mainstream right-wing [[Likud]]. There are also some left-wing Religious Zionists, such as Rabbi [[Michael Melchior]], whose views were represented by the [[Meimad]] party (which ran together with the [[Labor (Israel)|Israeli Labor party]]). Many Israeli [[Israeli settlements|settlers]] in the [[West Bank]] are Religious Zionists, along with most of the settlers forcibly expelled from the [[Gaza Strip]] in August and September 2005.\n\n== Military service ==\n{{unreferencedsect|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:IDF soldier put on tefillin.jpg|thumb|Second-Lieutenant [[From the Wilderness and Lebanon|Asael Lubotzky]], an [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] field commander during [[Second Lebanon War]], prays with [[Tefilin]]]]\nAll adult Jewish males in Israel are obligated to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]]. Certain segments of Orthodoxy defer their service in order to engage in full-time Torah study. Religious Zionist belief advocates that both are critical to Jewish survival and prosperity.\n\nFor this reason, many Religious Zionist men take part in the [[Hesder]] program, which allows military service to be combined with [[yeshiva]] studies. Some others attend a pre-army [[Mechina]] educational program, delaying their service by one year. 88% of Hesder students belong to combat units, compared to a national average of below 30%. \nStudents at Mercaz HaRav, and some Hardal yeshivot, undertake their Service through a modified form of Hesder.\n\nWhile some Religious Zionist women serve in the army, most choose national service, known as [[Sherut Leumi]], instead (working at hospitals, schools, and day-care centers).\nIn November 2010, the IDF held a special conference which was attended by the heads of Religious Zionism in order to encourage female Religious Zionists to join the IDF. The IDF undertook that all modesty and kosher issues will be handled in order to make female Religious Zionists comfortable.\n\n== Dress ==\nReligious Zionists are often called ''Kippot sruggot'', or \"sruggim\", referring to the knitted or crocheted ''[[kippot]]'' (skullcaps) worn by the men. (Many wear other types of headcoverings, such as black velvet ''kippot''.) \nTheir dress, otherwise, is largely the same as for secular Israelis; beards are uncommon, although mustaches are often seen in the older generations.\nWomen usually wear skirts, and often cover their hair.\nSee under [[Tzniut]]: [[Tzniut#Dress|#Dress]] and [[Tzniut#Hair covering|#Hair covering]].\n\nIn the ''Hardal'' community, the dress is generally more formal, with an emphasis on appearing neat.  \nThe Kippot, also knitted, are significantly larger, and it is common for [[tzitzit]] to be worn visibly, as is the [[Haredi]] practice; ''[[Payot]]'' (sidelocks) are similarly common, as is an (untrimmed) beard.\nWomen invariably cover their hair - usually with a [[snood]], or a ''mitpachat'' (Hebrew for \"kerchief\") - and often wear sandals.\n\nAt prayer, members of the community use the [[Koren Siddur]] or ''[[Rinat Yisrael]]''.\n\n== Notable figures ==\n* [[Yehuda Amital]]\n* [[Eli Sadan]] \n* [[Shlomo Aviner]]\n* [[Naftali Bennett]]\n* [[Yosef Burg]]\n* [[She'ar Yashuv Cohen]]\n* [[Haim Druckman]]\n* [[Effi Eitam]]\n* [[Mordechai Eliyahu]]\n* [[Moshe Feiglin]]\n* [[Shlomo Goren]]\n* [[Yitzhak HaLevi Herzog]]\n* [[Meir Kahane]]\n* [[Binyamin Ze'ev Kahane]]\n* [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]\n* [[Avraham Yitzchak Kook]]\n* [[Zvi Yehuda Kook]]\n* [[Dov Lior]]\n* [[Rafi Peretz]]\n* [[Zevulun Orlev]]\n* [[Shlomo Riskin]]\n* [[Avraham Shapira]]\n* [[Shaul Yisraeli]]\n* [[Oury Amos Cherki]]\n* [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n* [[Baruch Marzel]]\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]]\n* [[Baruch Goldstein]]\n* [[Yisrael Ariel]]\n* [[Yehuda Glick]]\n* [[Aharon Lichtenstein]]\n* [[Yaakov Ariel]]\n* [[Jonathan Sacks]]\n* [[Hanan Porat]]\n* [[Zvi Thau]]\n* [[Yaaqov Medan]]\n* [[Haim Sabato]]\n* [[Nahum Rabinovitch]]\n* [[Robert Aumann]]\n* [[Uri Orbach]]\n* [[Meir Bar-Ilan]]\n* [[Shimon Gershon Rosenberg]]\n* [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Hardal]]\n* [[Haredim and Zionism]]\n* [[Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Religion in Israel]]\n* [[Atchalta De'Geulah]]\n* [[Arutz Sheva]]\n* [[Hesder]]\n* [[Machon Meir]]\n* [[Mamlachti dati]]\n* [[Torato Omanuto]]\n* [[Torat Eretz Yisrael]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''The Zionist Idea and Its Variations'' by [[Shlomo Avineri]], ''Am Oved'' publishing, chapter 17: \"Rabbi Kook \u2013 the dialection in salvation\"\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Zionism an Affirmation of Judaism}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.rza.org/ Religious Zionists of America]\n* [http://therav.net/gallery/ReligiousZionists8.5x14V14.0.pdf Poster of Historic Religious Zionist Leaders]\n* [http://www.biu.ac.il/Spokesman/Tolerance/michman.htm A Historical Look at Religious Zionism] by Prof. Dan Michman\n* [http://www.shapell.org/manuscript.aspx?ben-gurion-peace Original Letters and Manuscripts: Zionism, Ben-Gurion on God's Promises] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://www.kipa.co.il/ \"Kipa \u2013 House of Religious Zionism\" (Hebrew)]\n* [http://www.mafdal.org.il/?sid=27 Official National Religious Party website (in English)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041216072651/http://www.mizrachi.org/ideas/view.asp?id=122 Religious Zionism And Modern Orthodoxy], Rav Yosef Blau\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050421213010/http://www.hagshama.org.il/en/resources/view.asp?id=1428 Religious Zionism, Compromise or Ideal?], hagshama.org.il\n* [http://www.afyba.org/ The American Friends of YBA \u2013 Supporters of religious Zionist educational movement in Israel]\n\n\n{{Religion in Israel}}\n{{Religious Zionism}}\n{{Zionism}}\n{{OrthodoxJudaism}}\n{{Jews and Judaism}}\n{{Relpolnav}}\n\n[[Category:Judaism-related controversies]]\n[[Category:Religious Zionism| ]]\n[[Category:Types of Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ideology that combines Zionism and Orthodox Judaism}}\n[[File:Kippot.jpg|thumb|Crocheted [[kippot]]]]\n[[File:PikiWiki Israel 7273 \u05e2\u05d9\u05df \u05d4\u05e0\u05e6\u05d9quot;\u05d1 \u05e2\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4 \u05dc\u05d4\u05ea\u05d9\u05d9\u05e9\u05d1\u05d5\u05ea.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionist pioneers found Kibbutz [[Ein HaNatziv]], 1946]]\n\n'''Religious Zionism''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05e6\u05b4\u05d9\u05bc\u05d5\u05b9\u05e0\u05d5\u05bc\u05ea \u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9\u05ea}}, [[Romanization of Hebrew|translit.]] ''Tziyonut Datit'', or {{Hebrew|\u05d3\u05b8\u05bc\u05ea\u05b4\u05d9 \u05dc\u05b0\u05d0\u05bb\u05de\u05b4\u05bc\u05d9}} ''Dati Leumi'' \"National Religious\", or {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b4\u05bc\u05e4\u05b8\u05bc\u05d4 \u05e1\u05b0\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d2\u05b8\u05d4}} ''Kippah seruga'', literally, \"knitted skullcap\") is an ideology that combines [[Zionism]] and [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\nBefore the establishment of [[Israel|the State of Israel]], Religious Zionists were mainly observant Jews who supported Zionist efforts to build a [[Jewish state]] in the [[Land of Israel]].\n\nAfter the [[Six-Day War]], and the capture of the [[West Bank]], a territory referred to in Jewish terms as [[Judea and Samaria]], right-wing components of the Religious Zionist movement integrated nationalist revindication{{explain|This term is not defined here, nor under the Ideology heading, and has no page or definition at the encyclopedia|date=July 2018}}, and evolved into [[Neo-Zionism]]. Their ideology revolves around three pillars: the Land of Israel, the People of Israel, and the Torah of Israel.<ref>[[Adriana Kemp]], ''Israelis in Conflict: Hegemonies, Identities, and Challenges'', Sussex Academic Press, 2004, pp.314\u2013315.</ref>\n\nThe [[Hardal]] (\u200e \u05d7\u05e8\u05d3\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d0\u05d5\u05de\u05d9 \u1e24aredi Le'umi, lit.\u2009\"Nationalist [[Haredi]]\") are a sub-community; stricter in observance, and more \"statist\" in their politics.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Abraham Isaac Kook 1924.jpg|thumb|[[Abraham Isaac Kook]], 1924]]\n\nIn 1862, German Orthodox [[Rabbi]] [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]] published his tractate ''Derishat Zion'', positing that the salvation of the Jews, promised by the [[Nevi'im|Prophets]], can come about only by self-help.<ref>[http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/view.jsp?artid=56&letter=K Zvi Hirsch Kalischer] (Jewish Encyclopedia)</ref> Rabbi [[Moshe Shmuel Glasner]] was another prominent rabbi who supported Zionism. The main ideologue of modern Religious Zionism was Rabbi [[Abraham Isaac Kook]], who justified Zionism according to [[Halakha|Jewish law]], and urged young religious Jews to support efforts to settle the land, and the secular [[Labour Zionist]]s to give more consideration to Judaism. Kook saw Zionism as a part of a divine scheme which would result in the resettlement of the Jewish people in its homeland. This would bring salvation (\"Geula\") to Jews, and then to the entire world. After world harmony is achieved by the refoundation of the Jewish homeland, the [[Messiah]] will come. Although this has not yet happened, Kook emphasized that it would take time, and that the ultimate redemption happens in stages, often not apparent while happening. In 1924, when Kook became the [[Ashkenazi]] [[Chief Rabbi]] of [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]], he tried to reconcile Zionism with [[Orthodox Judaism]].\n\n== Ideology ==\n[[File:Jerusalem Day.jpg|thumb|Religious Zionists celebrating [[Jerusalem Day]]]]\nReligious Zionists believe that \"[[Eretz Israel|Eretz Yisrael]]\" (the Land of Israel) was promised to the ancient [[Israelites]] by [[God in Judaism|God]].  Furthermore, modern Jews have the obligation to possess and defend the land in ways that comport with the [[Torah]]'s high standards of justice.<ref>Novak, David.  [https://mosaicmagazine.com/response/politics-current-affairs/2020/01/what-unites-people-of-faith-across-religions-and-divides-them-from-others/ \"What Unites People of Faith across Religions, and Divides Them from Others.\"] ''Mosaic''.  23 January 2020.  23 January 2020.</ref> To generations of [[Jewish diaspora|diaspora Jews]], [[Jerusalem]] has been a symbol of the [[Holy Land]] and of their return to it, as promised by God in numerous [[Bible|Biblical prophecies]]. Despite this, many Jews did not embrace Zionism before the 1930s, and certain religious groups opposed it then, as some groups still do now, on the grounds that an attempt to re-establish Jewish rule in Israel by [[human agency]] was blasphemous. Hastening salvation and the coming of the Messiah was considered religiously forbidden, and Zionism was seen as a sign of disbelief in God's power, and therefore, a rebellion against God. Rabbi Kook developed a [[theology|theological]] answer to that claim, which gave Zionism a religious legitimation: \"Zionism was not merely a political movement by secular Jews. It was actually a tool of [[God]] to promote His divine scheme, and to initiate the return of the Jews to their homeland \u2013 the land He promised to [[Abraham]], [[Isaac]], and [[Jacob]]. God wants the [[children of Israel]] to return to their home in order to establish a Jewish sovereign state in which Jews could live according to the laws of [[Torah]] and [[Halakha]], and commit the [[Mitzvah|Mitzvot]] of Eretz Israel (these are religious commandments which can be performed only in the [[Land of Israel]]). Moreover, to cultivate the Land of Israel was a Mitzvah by itself, and it should be carried out. Therefore, settling [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is an obligation of the religious Jews, and helping Zionism is actually following God's will.\"<ref>{{cite book |title=Torat Eretz Yisrael|first=David|last=Samson|author2=Tzvi Fishman |publisher=Torat Eretz Yisrael Publications|location=Jerusalem |year=1991}}</ref>\n\nReligious Jews also disapproved of the Zionists because many were secular Jews or [[atheist]]s, taking their cue from [[Marxism]]. [[Labour Zionism|Socialist Zionism]] envisaged the movement as a tool for building an advanced [[socialist]] society in the land of Israel, while solving the problem of [[antisemitism]]. The early [[kibbutz]] was a communal settlement that focused on national goals, unencumbered by religion and precepts of Jewish law such as [[kashrut]]. Socialist Zionists were one of the results of a long process of modernization within the Jewish communities of Europe, known as the [[Haskalah]], or Jewish Enlightenment. Rabbi Kook's answer was as follows:\n\n:''Secular Zionists may think they do it for political, national, or socialist reasons, but in fact \u2013 the actual reason for them coming to resettle in [[Eretz Israel|Israel]] is a religious Jewish spark (\"Nitzotz\") in their [[soul]], planted by God. Without their knowledge, they are contributing to the divine scheme and actually committing a great [[Mitzvah]].''\n\n:''The role of religious Zionists is to help them to establish a Jewish state and turn the religious spark in them into a great light. They should show them that the real source of Zionism and the longed-for Zion is [[Judaism]] and teach them [[Torah]] with love and kindness. In the end, they will understand that the laws of [[Torah]] are the key to true [[harmony]] and a [[socialist]] state (not in the [[Marxist]] [[Socialist mode of production|meaning]]) that will be a light for the [[goyim|nations]] and bring salvation to the world.''\n\n[[Shlomo Avineri]] explained the last part of Kook's answer: \"... and the end of those pioneers, who scout into the blindness of secularism and atheism, but the treasured light inside them leads them into the path of salvation \u2013 their end is that from doing Mitzva without purpose, they will do Mitzva with a purpose.\" (page 222, <sup>[[Religious Zionist Movement#References|1]]</sup>)\n\n== Organizations ==\n[[File:Bnei akiva logo.jpg|thumb|100px|left|[[Bnei Akiva]] youth movement, combining Torah and work]]\n\nThe first rabbis to support Zionism were [[Judah Alkalai|Yehuda Shlomo Alkalai]] and [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]. They argued that the change in the status of [[Western Europe]]'s Jews following [[Jewish emancipation|emancipation]] was the first step toward redemption (\u05d2\u05d0\u05d5\u05dc\u05d4), and that, therefore, one must hasten the messianic salvation by a natural salvation \u2013 whose main pillars are the [[Kibbutz Galuyot]] (\"Gathering of the Exiles\"), the return to Eretz Israel, agricultural work (\u05e2\u05d1\u05d5\u05d3\u05ea \u05d0\u05d3\u05de\u05d4), and the revival of the everyday use of the [[Hebrew language]].\n\nThe [[Mizrachi (Religious Zionism)|Mizrachi]] organization was established in 1902 in [[Vilna]] at a world conference of Religious Zionists. It operates a [[Zionist youth movement|youth movement]], [[Bnei Akiva]], which was founded in 1929. Mizrachi believes that the [[Torah]] should be at the centre of [[Zionism]], a sentiment expressed in the Mizrachi Zionist slogan ''Am Yisrael B'Eretz Yisrael al pi Torat Yisrael'' (\"The people of Israel in the land of Israel according to the Torah of Israel\"). It also sees Jewish nationalism as a tool for achieving religious objectives. Mizrachi was the first official Religious Zionist party. It also built a network of religious schools that exist to this day.\n\nIn 1937-1948, the [[Religious Kibbutz Movement]] established three settlement blocs of three kibbutzim each. The first was in the [[Beit Shean]] Valley, the second was in the [[Hebron]] mountains south of [[Bethlehem]] (known as [[Gush Etzion]]), and the third was in the western [[Negev]]. Kibbutz [[Yavne]] was founded in the center of the country as the core of a fourth bloc that came into being after the establishment of the state.<ref>\"Settlement clustering on a socio-cultural basis: The bloc settlement policy of the Religious Kibbutz Movement in Palestine,\" Yossi Katz, ''Journal of Rural Studies'', vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 161\u2013171, 1995</ref>\n\n== Political parties ==\nThe [[Labor Movement]] wing of Religious Zionism, founded in 1921 under the Zionist slogan \"Torah va'Avodah\" (Torah and Labor), was called [[Hapoel HaMizrachi]]. It represented religiously traditional [[Labour Zionism|Labour Zionists]], both in Europe and in the Land of Israel, where it represented religious Jews in the [[Histadrut]]. In 1956, Mizrachi, Hapoel HaMizrachi, and other religious Zionists formed the [[National Religious Party]] to advance the rights of religious Zionist Jews in Israel. Other parties and groups affiliated with religious Zionism are [[Gush Emunim]], [[Tkuma (political party)|Tkuma]], and [[Meimad]]. [[Kahanism]], a radical branch of religious Zionism, was founded by Rabbi [[Meir Kahane]], whose party, [[Kach and Kahane Chai|Kach]], was eventually banned for [[racism]]. Today, [[Otzma Yehudit]] is the leading wing of this school of thought.\n\n== Educational institutions ==\n:''See: [[Yeshiva #Israel]]; [[:Category:Religious Zionist yeshivot]]; [[List of Midrashot]].''\n[[File:Mercaz HaRav01.JPG|thumb|[[Mercaz Harav]], Jerusalem]]\nThe flagship religious institution of the Religious Zionist movement is the [[yeshiva]] founded by Rabbi Abraham Isaac Kook in 1924, called in his honor \"[[Mercaz haRav]]\" (lit., the Rabbi's center). \nOther Religious Zionist yeshivot include [[Ateret Cohanim]], [[Beit El yeshiva]] and Yeshivat [[Or Etzion]], founded by Rav [[Haim Druckman]], a foremost disciple of Rabbi [[Tzvi Yehuda Kook]].\n\nThere are also approximately 90 ''[[Hesder]]'' yeshivot, allowing students to continue [[Torah study]] during their National Service (see [[#Military_service|below]]).\nThe first was [[Yeshivat Kerem B'Yavneh]], established in 1954; the largest is the [[Hesder Yeshiva of Sderot]] with over 800 students.\nOthers well known include [[Machon Meir|Yeshivat Machon Meir]], [[Yeshivat Har Etzion]], [[Yeshivat HaKotel]], [[Yeshivat Birkat Moshe]] in [[Maale Adumim]], [[Yeshiva Har Bracha|Yeshivat Har Bracha]] and Yeshivat Har Hamor.  \n\nThese institutions usually offer a [[kollel]] for ''[[Semikha]]'', or Rabbinic ordination. Students generally prepare for the ''Semikha'' test of the [[Chief Rabbinate of Israel]]; often for that of the [[posek]] R. [[Zalman Nechemia Goldberg]].\nTraining as a [[Dayan (rabbinic judge)]] in this community is usually through [[:he:\u05de\u05db\u05d5\u05df \u05d0\u05e8\u05d9\u05d0\u05dc|''Machon Ariel'']] (''[[Machon Harry Fischel]]''), also founded by Rav Kook, or [[:he:\u05d0\u05e8\u05e5_\u05d7\u05de\u05d3\u05d4_(\u05db\u05d5\u05dc\u05dc) |''Kollel Eretz Hemda'']].\n\nWomen study in institutions known as ''Midrashot'' (sing. [[Midrasha]]) - examples are [[Ein_HaNetziv#Education|Ein HaNatziv Women's Seminary]] and [[Migdal Oz (seminary)|Migdal Oz]]. Some also offer degree studies (and may then be known as a ''machon'').\n[[Nishmat (midrasha)|Nishmat]] trains women as [[Yoetzet Halacha|Yoatzot Halacha]]; see also [[Midreshet Lindenbaum]] and [[Matan Women's Institute for Torah Studies|Matan]], which similarly offer Talmud focused learning to women.\n\nHigh school students study at [[Education_in_Israel#Educational_tracks|''Mamlachti dati'']] schools, often associated with ''[[Bnei Akiva]]''. The first of these was at [[Kfar Haroeh]] established by [[Moshe-Zvi Neria]]. A girls' high school is referred to as an ''[[Ulpana]]''.\nFor degree studies, many attend [[Bar Ilan University]], which allows students to combine Yeshiva studies with university study; \n[[Jerusalem College of Technology]] similarly (which also offers a Haredi track).\nThere are also [[List_of_Israeli_universities_and_colleges#Colleges|several colleges of education]] associated with Hesder and the ''Midrashot'', such as [[Herzog College]] and the [[Lifshitz College of Education]]. These often allow specializations in [[Tanach]] and ''Machshava'' ([[Jewish thought]]).\n\nSome institutions are aligned with the ''Hardal'' community, with an ideology that is somewhat more \"statist\".\nThe leading Yeshiva here is [[Har Hamor]]; [[Hardal#Schools|several high schools]] also operate.\n\n== Politics ==\nMost Religious Zionists embrace [[right-wing]] politics, especially the religious right-wing [[Jewish Home]] party, but also support the mainstream right-wing [[Likud]]. There are also some left-wing Religious Zionists, such as Rabbi [[Michael Melchior]], whose views were represented by the [[Meimad]] party (which ran together with the [[Labor (Israel)|Israeli Labor party]]). Many Israeli [[Israeli settlements|settlers]] in the [[West Bank]] are Religious Zionists, along with most of the settlers forcibly expelled from the [[Gaza Strip]] in August and September 2005.\n\n== Military service ==\n{{unreferencedsect|date=November 2015}}\n[[File:IDF soldier put on tefillin.jpg|thumb|Second-Lieutenant [[From the Wilderness and Lebanon|Asael Lubotzky]], an [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]] field commander during [[Second Lebanon War]], prays with [[Tefilin]]]]\nAll adult Jewish males in Israel are obligated to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces|IDF]]. Certain segments of Orthodoxy defer their service in order to engage in full-time Torah study. Religious Zionist belief advocates that both are critical to Jewish survival and prosperity.\n\nFor this reason, many Religious Zionist men take part in the [[Hesder]] program, which allows military service to be combined with [[yeshiva]] studies. Some others attend a pre-army [[Mechina]] educational program, delaying their service by one year. 88% of Hesder students belong to combat units, compared to a national average of below 30%. \nStudents at Mercaz HaRav, and some Hardal yeshivot, undertake their Service through a modified form of Hesder.\n\nWhile some Religious Zionist women serve in the army, most choose national service, known as [[Sherut Leumi]], instead (working at hospitals, schools, and day-care centers).\nIn November 2010, the IDF held a special conference which was attended by the heads of Religious Zionism in order to encourage female Religious Zionists to join the IDF. The IDF undertook that all modesty and kosher issues will be handled in order to make female Religious Zionists comfortable.\n\n== Dress ==\nReligious Zionists are often called ''Kippot sruggot'', or \"sruggim\", referring to the knitted or crocheted ''[[kippot]]'' (skullcaps) worn by the men. (Many wear other types of headcoverings, such as black velvet ''kippot''.) \nTheir dress, otherwise, is largely the same as for secular Israelis; beards are uncommon.\nWomen usually wear skirts, and often cover their hair.\nSee under [[Tzniut]]: [[Tzniut#Dress|#Dress]] and [[Tzniut#Hair covering|#Hair covering]].\n\nIn the ''Hardal'' community, the dress is generally more formal, with an emphasis on appearing neat.  \nThe Kippot, also knitted, are significantly larger, and it is common for [[tzitzit]] to be worn visibly, as is the [[Haredi]] practice; ''[[Payot]]'' (sidelocks) are similarly common, as is an (untrimmed) beard.\nWomen invariably cover their hair - usually with a [[snood]], or a ''mitpachat'' (Hebrew for \"kerchief\") - and often wear sandals.\n\nAt prayer, members of the community use the [[Koren Siddur]] or ''[[Rinat Yisrael]]''.\n\n== Notable figures ==\n* [[Yehuda Amital]]\n* [[Eli Sadan]] \n* [[Shlomo Aviner]]\n* [[Naftali Bennett]]\n* [[Yosef Burg]]\n* [[She'ar Yashuv Cohen]]\n* [[Haim Druckman]]\n* [[Effi Eitam]]\n* [[Mordechai Eliyahu]]\n* [[Moshe Feiglin]]\n* [[Shlomo Goren]]\n* [[Yitzhak HaLevi Herzog]]\n* [[Meir Kahane]]\n* [[Binyamin Ze'ev Kahane]]\n* [[Zvi Hirsch Kalischer]]\n* [[Avraham Yitzchak Kook]]\n* [[Zvi Yehuda Kook]]\n* [[Dov Lior]]\n* [[Rafi Peretz]]\n* [[Zevulun Orlev]]\n* [[Shlomo Riskin]]\n* [[Avraham Shapira]]\n* [[Shaul Yisraeli]]\n* [[Oury Amos Cherki]]\n* [[Bezalel Smotrich]]\n* [[Baruch Marzel]]\n* [[Michael Ben-Ari]]\n* [[Baruch Goldstein]]\n* [[Yisrael Ariel]]\n* [[Yehuda Glick]]\n* [[Aharon Lichtenstein]]\n* [[Yaakov Ariel]]\n* [[Jonathan Sacks]]\n* [[Hanan Porat]]\n* [[Zvi Thau]]\n* [[Yaaqov Medan]]\n* [[Haim Sabato]]\n* [[Nahum Rabinovitch]]\n* [[Robert Aumann]]\n* [[Uri Orbach]]\n* [[Meir Bar-Ilan]]\n* [[Shimon Gershon Rosenberg]]\n* [[Joseph B. Soloveitchik]]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Hardal]]\n* [[Haredim and Zionism]]\n* [[Modern Orthodox Judaism]]\n* [[Religion in Israel]]\n* [[Atchalta De'Geulah]]\n* [[Arutz Sheva]]\n* [[Hesder]]\n* [[Machon Meir]]\n* [[Mamlachti dati]]\n* [[Torato Omanuto]]\n* [[Torat Eretz Yisrael]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''The Zionist Idea and Its Variations'' by [[Shlomo Avineri]], ''Am Oved'' publishing, chapter 17: \"Rabbi Kook \u2013 the dialection in salvation\"\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikisourcepar|Zionism an Affirmation of Judaism}}\n{{commonscat}}\n* [http://www.rza.org/ Religious Zionists of America]\n* [http://therav.net/gallery/ReligiousZionists8.5x14V14.0.pdf Poster of Historic Religious Zionist Leaders]\n* [http://www.biu.ac.il/Spokesman/Tolerance/michman.htm A Historical Look at Religious Zionism] by Prof. Dan Michman\n* [http://www.shapell.org/manuscript.aspx?ben-gurion-peace Original Letters and Manuscripts: Zionism, Ben-Gurion on God's Promises] Shapell Manuscript Foundation\n* [http://www.kipa.co.il/ \"Kipa \u2013 House of Religious Zionism\" (Hebrew)]\n* [http://www.mafdal.org.il/?sid=27 Official National Religious Party website (in English)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20041216072651/http://www.mizrachi.org/ideas/view.asp?id=122 Religious Zionism And Modern Orthodoxy], Rav Yosef Blau\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050421213010/http://www.hagshama.org.il/en/resources/view.asp?id=1428 Religious Zionism, Compromise or Ideal?], hagshama.org.il\n* [http://www.afyba.org/ The American Frien