the West: The Kirkuk-Banias Oil Pipeline has been closed and the Iraqi portion reported unusable since the 2003 war in Iraq. Discussions were held between Iraqi and Syrian government officials to re-open the pipeline, which had a design capacity of 700,000 bbl/d, although actual volumes never reached this level. The Russian company [[Stroytransgaz]] accepted an offer to fix the pipeline in December 2007, but no follow-up was made. Iraq and Syria have discussed building several new pipelines, including a 1.5 million bbl/d pipeline carrying heavy crude oil, and a 1.25 million bbl/d pipeline for carrying light crudes. To the South: The 1.65 million bbl/d Iraq Pipeline to Saudi Arabia (IPSA) has been closed since 1991 following the Persian Gulf War. There are no plans to reopen this line.\nIraq has also held discussions to build a crude oil pipeline from [[Haditha]] to Jordan's [[port of Aqaba]].\n\n====Ports====\n[[File:Iraq seaborne crude oil exports by destination in 2017 (31760972217).png|upright=1.4|thumb|Destination of Iraqi seaborne exports of crude oil in 2017]]\nThe [[Basra Oil Terminal]] on the Persian Gulf has an effective capacity to load 1.3 million bbl/d and support [[Very Large Crude Carriers]]. In February 2009, the South Oil Company commissioned Foster Wheeler to carry out the basic engineering design to rehabilitate and expand capacity of the terminal by building four single point mooring systems with a capacity of 800,000 bbl/d each. According to former Minister of Oil Issam al-Chalabi, it would take at least until 2013 to complete the project if financing is found.\nThere are five smaller ports on the Persian Gulf, all functioning at less than full capacity, including the Khor al-Amaya terminal.\n\n====Overland export routes====\nOverland routes are used to export limited amounts of crude from small fields bordering Syria. In addition, Iraq has resumed shipping oil to Jordan's [[Zarqa]]\nrefinery by road tankers at a rate of 10,000 bbl/d.\n\n===Downstream===\nEstimates of Iraqi nameplate refining capacity vary, from 637,500 bbl/d according to the Oil and Gas Journal to 790,000 bbl/d according to the Special Inspector General for Iraqi Reconstruction. Iraqi refineries have antiquated infrastructure and only half run at utilization rates of 50 percent or more. Despite improvements in recent years, the sector has not been able to meet domestic demand of about 600,000 bbl/d, and the refineries produce too much heavy fuel oil and not enough other refined products. As a result, Iraq relies on imports for 30 percent of its gasoline and 17 percent of its LPG.\nTo alleviate product shortages, Iraq's 10-year strategic plan for 2008-2017 set a goal of increasing refining capacity to 1.5 million bbl/d, and is seeking $20 billion in investments to achieve this target. Iraq has plans for 4 new refineries, as well as plans for expanding the existing Daura and Basra refineries.\n\n== Natural gas ==\n\n=== Upstream ===\n\n====Gas production====\nIraqi natural gas production rose from to 81 (billion) Bcf in 2003 to 522 Bcf in 2008. Some is used as fuel for power generation, and some is re-injected to enhance oil recovery. Over 40 percent of the production in 2008 was flared due to a lack of sufficient infrastructure to utilize it for consumption and export, although [[Royal Dutch Shell]] estimated that flaring losses were even greater at 1 Bcf per day. As a result, Iraq's five natural gas processing plants, which can process over 773 billion cubic feet per year, sit mostly idle. To reduce flaring, Iraq has been working on an agreement with Royal Dutch Shell to implement a 25-year project to capture flared gas and provide it for domestic use. Iraq's cabinet gave preliminary approval for the $17 billion deal covering development of 25\u201330 Tcf of associated natural gas reserves in Basra province through a new joint venture, [[Basra Gas Company]]. The agreement, which originally was to cover all of [[Basra Governorate]], has been modified to include only the associated gas from the Rumaila, Zubair, and West Qurna Phase I projects. Implementation of this agreement is necessary for the new oil development projects to go forward.\n\n====Upstream development====\nIraq has planned an upstream bidding round in late 2010 for three non-associated natural gas fields with combined reserves of over 7.5 Tcf. This will be the third hydrocarbon bidding round conducted by Iraq, following two earlier rounds that were held to develop Iraq's oil fields. All of the companies that prequalified to bid in the two earlier rounds will be invited. Iraq has committed to purchasing 100 percent of the gas.\n\n=== Midstream ===\nPlans to export natural gas remain controversial due to the amount of idle and sub-optimally fired electricity generation capacity in Iraq\u2014much a result of a lack of adequate gas feedstock. Prior to the 1990\u20131991 [[Gulf War]], Iraq exported natural gas to Kuwait. The gas came from Rumaila through a {{convert|105|mile|km}} pipeline with a capacity of {{convert|400|e6ft3|e6m3|abbr=off}} per day to Kuwait's central processing center at [[Al Ahmadi, Kuwait|Kuwait]]. In 2007, the Ministry of Oil announced an agreement to fund a feasibility study on the revival of the mothballed pipeline. Iraq has eyed northern export routes such as the proposed [[Nabucco pipeline]] through Turkey to [[Europe]], and in July 2009 Prime Minister [[Nouri al-Maliki]] suggested that Iraq could be exporting 530 Bcf per year to Europe by 2015. A second option is the [[Arab Gas Pipeline]] (AGP) project. The proposed AGP pipeline would deliver gas from Iraq's Akkas field to Syria and then on to [[Lebanon]] and the Turkish border sometime in 2010, and then on to Europe. Other proposals have included building LNG exporting facilities in the Basra region.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Iraq|Energy|Companies}}\n*[[Economy of Iraq]]\n*[[Energy in Iraq]]\n*[[Oil reserves in Iraq]]\n*[[Iraq National Oil Company]]\n*[[South Oil Company]]\n*[[Missan Oil Company]]\n*[[Midland Oil Company]]\n*[[North Oil Company]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Middle East topic|Petroleum industry in}}\n[[Category:Petroleum industry in Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "Januarythefifteenth", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed some punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petroleum_industry_in_Iraq"}
{"title_page": "Rudratej Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian business executive}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rudratej Singh\n| image              = Rudratej Singh during an auto event.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = 1973 or 1974\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = {{death date and given age|2020|4|20|46|df=y}}\n| death_place        = \n| resting_place      = \n| nationality        = Indian\n| citizenship        = Indian\n| other_names        = \n| known_for          = Career in [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors]] and [[Unilever]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]]<br>[[Delhi University]]<br>[[IMT Ghaziabad]]\n| employer           = [[BMW India]]\n| occupation         = [[CEO]], [[President (corporate title)|President]]\n| years_active       = \n| home_town          = \n| networth           = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n}}\n\n'''Rudratej Singh''' (1973 or 1974 \u2013 20 April 2020) was an Indian business executive. He was the first Indian \nPresident and CEO of [[BMW India]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/sectors/auto/former-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-to-now-lead-bmw-india/story/357547.html|title=Former Royal Enfield chief Rudratej Singh to now lead BMW India|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/auto-news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1560945636948.html|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield boss, to head BMW India|last=Panday|first=Amit|date=2019-06-19|website=Livemint.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> Singh was known for his former positions as Global President of [[Royal Enfield (India)|Royal Enfield Motors Limited]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://auto.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/industry/bmw-appoints-ex-royal-enfield-chief-rudratej-singh-appointed-as-president-ceo-of-india-operations/69859474|title=Ex-Royal Enfield sales head Rudratej Singh appointed as President & CEO of BMW Group India - ET Auto|website=[[The Economic Times]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and Vice President of [[Unilever]] in Singapore.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Early life and education==\nSingh grew up in New Delhi. He completed his schooling from [[Air Force Bal Bharati School]], batch of 1990. He graduated in Commerce from [[Delhi University]] in 1993 and then moved on to the [[IMT Ghaziabad]] to study MBA in Marketing and Finance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inshorts.com/en/news/rudratej-singh-former-royal-enfield-president-to-head-bmw-india-1561001423685|title=Rudratej Singh, former Royal Enfield President, to head BMW India|website=Inshorts - Stay Informed|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> In 2014, he undertook Advanced Management Program from [[Harvard Business School]].\n\n==Career==\nSingh started his career in 1996 as a Senior Product Manager at the [[Dabur|Dabur India Limited]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.autoactu.com/rudratej-singh-nomme-president-directeur-general-de-bmw-group-inde.shtml|title=autoactu.com - l'information automobile professionnelle|website=www.autoactu.com|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He then joined as Area Sales Manager in [[Hindustan Unilever]] in August 1998. In 2000, he was then promoted to Sr Brand Manager, within Hindustan Unilever,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/magazine/event/business-today-honda-pro-am-of-champions-event/story/12884.html|title=Happy Valley- Business News|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> where he was one of the key people to create the Brooke Bond master brand. He then held senior positions in the Hindustan Unilever Ltd and Unilever PLC across various developed and developing markets globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/company-officers/EICH.NSf|title=${Instrument_CompanyName} ${Instrument_Ric} People {{!}} Reuters.com|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|website=U.S.|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/companies/rudratej-singh-appointed-bmw-group-india-president-and-chief-executive-119061901266_1.html|title=Rudratej Singh appointed BMW Group India President and Chief Executive|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|date=2019-06-19|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn Jan 2015, he moved from Unilever and joined Eicher Motors Limited (EML) as their President of flagship motorcycle business, Royal Enfield and member of the Management Team of [[Eicher Motors|Eicher Motors Limited]] (EML).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-quits-royal-enfield-with-immediate-effect/|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield with immediate effect|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>  In 2017, Singh was promoted to the Global President of Royal Enfield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moneycontrol.com/news/business/bmw-group-names-rudratej-singh-as-president-and-ceo-for-india-4116681.html|title=BMW Group names Rudratej Singh as president and CEO for India|website=Moneycontrol|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president/articleshow/45929893.cms|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|date=2015-01-19|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/auto/auto-news/story/royal-enfield-sets-up-direct-sales-subsidiary-in-the-us-plans-to-open-retail-stores-288812-2015-08-18|title=Royal Enfield sets up direct sales subsidiary in the US; plans to open retail stores|last=DelhiAugust 18|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=August 18|first2=2015UPDATED|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|last3=Ist|first3=2015 10:19}}</ref> During his four year tenure, he helped Royal Enfield become one of the most profitable auto companies in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/companies/royal-enfields-rudratej-singh-quits/article25941078.ece|title=Rudratej Singh quits Royal Enfield|last=PTI|website=@businessline|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.forbesindia.com/article/super-50-companies-2015/eicher-motors-its-all-in-the-drive/40705/1|title=Eicher Motors: It's all in the drive|website=Forbes India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> His efforts also helped grow the company\u2019s market share in India from 3.3%, in 2014, to 6.9%, in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eicher.in/uploads/1518004619_press-release-eicher-motors-results-Q3-2017-18.pdf|title=Eicher Motors Limited registers record performance in the quarter ended December 31st, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloombergquint.com/markets/eicher-motors-stock-jumps-on-plan-to-increase-royal-enfield-capacity|title=Eicher Motors' Stock Jumps On Plan To Increase Royal Enfield Capacity|website=BloombergQuint|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Singh quit Royal Enfield after serving for four years<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/two-wheelers/royal-enfield-president-rudratej-singh-quits-lalit-malik-to-take-charge/articleshow/67438710.cms|title=Royal Enfield President Rudratej Singh quits, Lalit Malik to take charge|date=2019-01-08|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarpro.in/News/royal-enfield\u2019s-president-rudratej-singh-quits-41770|title=Royal Enfield's president Rudratej Singh quits|website=Autocarpro.in|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> and joined BMW India as its President and Chief Executive Officer (CEO) with his term starting from August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zeebiz.com/automobile/news-bmw-group-india-gets-new-ceo-who-is-rudratej-rudy-singh-profile-102807|title=BMW Group India gets new CEO - Who is Rudratej 'Rudy' Singh? Profile|date=2019-06-19|website=Zee Business|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.afaqs.com/people-spotting/463_Former-Enfield-hand-Rudratej-Singh-joins-BMW-India-as-president-and-CEO|title=Former Enfield hand Rudratej Singh joins BMW India as president and CEO|date=2019-06-23|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://auto.ndtv.com/news/rudratej-singh-appointed-president-and-ceo-of-bmw-group-india-2055903|title=Rudratej Singh Appointed President And CEO Of BMW Group India - NDTV CarAndBike|website=CarAndBike|language=English|access-date=2019-07-01}}</ref> He died on 20 April 2020 at the age of 46 from cardiac arrest.<ref>[http://everythingexperiential.businessworld.in/article/Rudratej-Singh-President-CEO-of-BMW-Group-India-is-no-more/20-04-2020-189621/ Rudratej Singh, President & CEO of BMW Group India is no more]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/bmw-india-ceo-rudratej-singh-passes-away-due-to-cardiac-arrest/articleshow/75251335.cms|title=Rudratej Singh: BMW India CEO Rudratej Singh passes away due to cardiac arrest {{!}} India Business News - Times of India|last=Apr 20|first=PTI {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23|last3=Ist|first3=23:33}}</ref>\n\n== Other activities ==\nSingh represented India as an amateur golfer and won 18 titles globally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://overdrive.in/news-cars-auto/rudratej-singh-appointed-as-new-president-of-royal-enfield/|title=Rudratej Singh appointed as new president of Royal Enfield|website=Overdrive|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He was also a board member of the Women\u2019s Golf Association of India (WGAI),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/golfdigestindia/docs/gd_02_2018/34|title=Golf Digest India - February 2018|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> and helped run a charity for underprivileged (girl) children.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cmocouncil.org/profiles/7486|title=Members - CMO Council\u2122|website=www.cmocouncil.org|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref> He spoke regularly at various business and brand forums across the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autocarindia.com/bike-news/rudratej-singh-is-royal-enfield8217s-new-president-392882|title=Rudratej Singh is Royal Enfield's new President|website=Autocar India|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 2012 - Marketer of the Year by the World CMO Council - Asia<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiainfoline.com/article/news-top-story/royal-enfield-appoints-rudratej-singh-as-president-115011900010_1.html|title=Royal Enfield appoints Rudratej Singh as President|website=www.indiainfoline.com|language=en|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n*2007 - Hindustan Unilever Directors Award<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/hul-allcargo-top-honchos-win-the-last-leg-of-et-golf/articleshow/5635162.cms?from=mdr|title=HUL, Allcargo top honchos win the last leg of ET golf|date=2010-03-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2019-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Rudratej}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:BMW people]]\n[[Category:Institute of Management Technology, Ghaziabad alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Delhi alumni]]\n[[Category:Place of death missing]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School Advanced Management Program attendees]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian business executive}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rudratej Singh\n| image              = Rudratej Singh during an au